Just in itself, Christianity is divided into 25 different &quot;sects.&quot; Which one is right? This causes tension between the sects, and of course, between different religions on who believes or thinks who is right or wrong.<br>
In an idealistic world, people would live in the present, and just exist. Our inner desires to continue, and to seek out eternal personal gratification however, and the fear of losing our &quot;possesions&quot; (material or self), make us cling to these religions. A greater sense of security in an insecure world, where fear is supressed by the hope, not fact, that humans exist eternally.<br>
Some parts of religions state to be good, and not do bad things, but those are the rules learned from the society you live in. Religions only trap people in their own prisonhouses of belief, instead of freeing the soul and experiencing the undefinable, such as love.<br>
Being a good human being in general is much more important than paying your way into some afterlife and condemning those who do not believe and think the way you do.<br>
